Base unit
=========

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SI_base_unit
length m, mass kg, time s, ampere A, kelvin K, mole mol, candela cd

Second: Radiation of the caesium 133 atom
Metre: from c
Kilogram: prototype
Kelvin: 1K= the fraction 1⁄273.16 of the thermodynamic temperature of the triple point of water.
mole: nombre d'atomes dans 0.012 kilogram of carbon 12

Ampere: The ampere is that constant current which, if maintained in two straight parallel conductors of infinite length, of negligible circular cross-section, and placed 1 metre apart in vacuum, would produce between these conductors a force equal to 2 × 10−7 newton per metre of length.

Candela: The candela is the luminous intensity, in a given direction, of a source that emits monochromatic radiation of frequency 540×1012 hertz and that has a radiant intensity in that direction of  1⁄683 watt per steradian.

Derived unit
============

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SI_derived_unit

Newton: 1N=1kg*1m/s²
Watt: 1W=1J/1s=1A*1V
Joule: 1J=1kg m²/s²= 1N*1m =1Pa.m^3 =1W.s=1 C.V
Pascal: 1Pa=1N/1m²
Coulomb: 1C=1A*1s=1F*1V
Volt: 1V=1W/1A=1J/1C (potential energy/charge)=kg⋅m^2⋅s^−3⋅A^−1
Ampere: 1A=1C/1s
Ohm: 1\Omega=1V/1A
Farad: 1F=1C/1V=1s/\Omega
Henri: 1H=1V/(1A/1s)=1\Omega.s
Weber (magnetic flux): 1Wb/m²=1T
Tesla: 1N=1T*1m/s*1C; 1T=1kg/Cs
Gray (dose of radiation), Sievert (equivalent dose): 1J/1kg
Lumen: 1 lm = 1 cd ⋅ sr (steradian)

