katal 	kat 	catalytic activity 	mol/s 	s−1⋅mol

# Constants
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physical_constant

- G=9.80665 m/s^2 (gravitational constant)
   F = G m_1 m_2 /r^2

- Coulomb constant: k_e = 1/4πε0 = 8.9875517873681764×10^9 m/F
  F = k_e q_1 q_2 /r^2

- 1 (metric) Horse power: lift 75 kilograms by 1 meter in 1 second=75*G=735.5W

- 1 cal is the approximate amount of energy needed to raise the temperature of one gram of water by one degree Celsius at a pressure of one atmosphere = 4.184J
  1 Cal=1kcal

# Quantum constants (with the future redefinition of SI units)

- Plank constant: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Planck_constant
  E=hf, h=6.62606X×10−34 J.s, f fréquence 
   =ℏω wtih ω=2πf the angular frequency and ℏ=h/2π
- Planck length l_P = \sqrt{ℏG/c^3} =1.616 199(97) × 10−35 m
- Planck mass m_P = \sqrt{ℏc/G} =2.176 51(13) × 10−8 kg
- Planck time t_P=l_P/c = ℏ/m_Pc^2 =5.391 06(32) × 10−44 s
- Planck charge q_P = \sqrt{4πε0ℏc} =1.875 545 956(41) × 10−18 C
- Planck temperature T_P = m_Pc^2/k_B =1.416 833(85) × 10^32 K

- von Klitzing constant RK = h/e^2 = 25812.807557(18) Ω (quantum hall effect)
- Φ_0 = h/(2e) ≈ 2.067833831(13)×10−15 Wb (magnetic flux quantum); K_J:=1/Φ_0 :=the Josephson constant
- boltzman constant k=1.38064852(79)×10−23 J⋅K−1
  p V = N k T, p pressure, V volume, N nombre d'atomes, T température

- electron mass m_e=2hR_\infty / c\alpha^2 =9.10938356×10-31 kilograms
- electron charge e=1.60217X× 10−19 coulomb (C).
- electron volt 1eV=1e*1v=1.6217X×10−19J

ε0 μ0 c^2=1
- µ0 =~ 4π×10−7 H.m-1 (H.m-1=N.A^-2) (magnetic constant) = 2hα/ce^2
- ε0 = 8.854 187 817... × 10−12 F·m−1
- Impedance of free space Z0=E/H=μ0 c=\sqrt{μ0/ε0}≈ 376.73031346177…Ω.
- Fine structure constant α: 4πε0ħcα = e^2; α=(e/q_P)^2
  α^−1 = 137.035999139(31).

- 1 dalton (Da)= 1M (molar mass constant) =~ 1g/mol; mass of a nucleon

# Redefinition of the SI units

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proposed_redefinition_of_SI_base_units
The kilogram, ampere, kelvin and mole will be redefined by choosing exact numerical values for the Planck constant, the elementary electric charge, the Boltzmann constant, and the Avogadro constant, respectively:
- The Planck constant h is exactly 6.62606X×10−34 joule second (J·s).
- The elementary charge e is exactly 1.60217X× 10−19 coulomb (C).
- The Boltzmann constant k is exactly 1.38065X×10−23 joule per kelvin (J·K−1).
- The Avogadro constant NA is exactly 6.02214X×10^23 reciprocal mole (mol−1).

Constants already defined:
- The speed of light c is exactly 299792458metres per second (m·s−1).
- The ground state hyperfine splitting frequency of the caesium-133 atom Δν(133Cs)hfs is exactly 9192631770 hertz (Hz).
- The luminous efficacy Kcd of monochromatic radiation of frequency 540×1012Hz is exactly 683 lumen per watt (lm·W−1).

Constants that were exactly defined but will not be:
- µ0 = 4π×10−7 N.A^-2 (from the ampere)
